    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.5.6-7_0001" />
                
                <fw type="curatorial">6</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">JOHN GALEN HOWARD
                        <lb/>
                    ARCHITECT</hi>
                
                    <hi rend="caps">JOHN GALEN HOWARD
                        <lb/>
                    ______
                        <lb/>
                    WILLIAM OTIS RAIGUEL</hi>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">ATLAS BUILDING
                        <lb/>
                    604 MISSION STREET
                        <lb/>
                    SAN FRANCISCO</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>January 23, 1918.</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>John G. Neihardt, Esq.,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Bancroft,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Nebraska.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I had the pleasure of receiving your note of January fifth on my return to Carmel just after I worte you last, and am now informed by the Secretary to the President of the University of California that your date at Berkely has been fixed for the evening of Monday, March fourth.</p>
                
                <p>As you are to read at Stanford on the twenty-sixth of February, and as that is on the way from San Francisco to Carmel, can you not spend the intervening time with us at the latter place? We could come up to town together on Sunday, the third, so that you would be in plenty of time for the reading at Berkeley. I hope I may also have the pleasure of meeting you when you arrive from the East and see that you are comfortably settled either at one of the clubs or at the hotel, as best suits your convenience.</p>
                
                <p>I am glad to know that your subject will be "The Western Epos." I had some talk the other evening with Professor Gayley, who is to preside and introduce you, and he spoke very enthusiastically of your work.
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.5.6-7_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">7</fw>
                    
                    <fw type="authorial">John G. Neihardt, Esq., ........... January 23, 1918. Page 2.</fw>
                
                From what he says you have enjoyed a great success with his men students. In these war times I am afraid your audience may be somewhat feminine in complexion, as, in fact, most audiences hereabouts now are. You will not be daunted by that, however.</p>
                
                <p>I am anticipating the keenest pleasure in seeing you again and hearing your work. If "The Song of Three Friends" works out as it promised in the parts you read to me it will be the biggest thing an American poet has done. My Pheidias forges ahead, and two or three people, whose judgment I trust, to whom I have read it, encourage me mightily. I sincerely hope you will feel the same.</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>With best wishes,</salute>
                    <salute>Faithfully yours,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>John Howard</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript><p>Most cordial greetings to all your "women folks" please. And I hope this railway congestion will be over by the time you start.</p></postscript>
                
            </div1>
